description.undefined: This ontology describes how data that has to be stored for a longer period of time within the built environment should be structured. The ontology is part of the Durable Data Storage System project, which is developed as part of a graduation thesis of the MSc. Construction Management and Engineering at Eindhoven University of Technology.
The object is accessible by anyone.
The object can be accessed by specific (groups of) people.
Asset Information Model. A model that contains all information related to a certain asset in the built environment as defined by ISO 19650.
Information that describes how other information is structured. Required by the OAIS standard for durable data storage.
A package of information submitted to an AIM at a single point in time, as described by ISO 19650. A data drop is usually trigerred by an event.
The acquistion of an asset, the transfer of an asset from the construction to the operational phase, or the transfer of ownership of an asset.
An interaction between an actor (person) and a document. There are multiple types of document interactions. Every document interaction is part of a data drop.

The copy of a document in its original file format. This copy in original format might help restoring data when something went wrong with transforming the document in question into an open file format.
A document interaction where the status of a document is changed.
The object is shared to a specific internal person.
Any event that relates to the operation of a building, such as cleaning, waste management, catering, etc.
Major changes or adaptions of an asset.
The document is being worked on, and is only accessible to those working on it.
The object is only shared to the internal team working on it.
Large repairs and reparations, improvements, and upgrades to maintain an asset in its optimal state.
Alphanumerical Information on a building or part of a building, as described by ISO 19650.
Information describing (part of) a building as described by ISO 19650.

Any object that is present in the real world. Here defined by the BOT ontology. Objects do not have to be physical (i.e., a space can be a physical object) but it does need to have a geometrical shape in the real world.
The disposal, decommissioning, demolition, or tranfer of ownership of an asset.
The object is shared to a specific external party.
Any type of changes or inspections of an asset during its lifespan.
Any event that relates to an asset, and about which information should be stored within an AIM. An event can be planned (i.e., the delivery of a building) or unplanned (i.e., damage to the asset).
An 'archived' document has been published, but is no longer relevant. It cannot be changed.
A document interaction where a new document is created.
The people or parties who can access a specific object.
A digital document which contains information and which can be shared with others in the form of a document.
Information describing the geometry of a building or part of a building, as described by ISO 19650. Usually stored in the form of an IFC model or other BIM model.
A document interaction where a new version of an existing document is uploaded.
Planned and unplanned maintenance on an asset.
The status of a document as described by ISO 19650.
The type of content that a document contains, as defined by ISO 19650.
Changes to an asset where parts of the building, or functions of the building, significantly change.
A published document can be accessed by others, and is final. In general it will not be updated.
Any human being.
An object that contains information about (part of) an asset.
A shared document can be accessed by others, but is still work in progress. New versions are to be expected.
The object is shared to a specific internal group.
Any object, either in the form of a physical object or an information object, that is part of the AIM in question.
Inspection of an asset where some aspect of a building is inspected, but not changed.
Measuring and sureveying (part of) an asset.
